# User-defined symbolic infix operators on JS (js-symbolic-infix-op)

Regression for two JS codegen bugs found via the examples sweep (parser-combinator
DSLs — dsl-ast-builder/dsl-calc-parser). A user-defined SYMBOLIC extension operator
(`<~>`, `~~`, `~>`, `<~`, `++`, …) is a method call in ssc, but JsGen (1) named the
extension function `_ext_T_<sym>` with the raw symbol — not a valid JS identifier, a
parse-time SyntaxError — and (2) emitted the infix USE as a raw JS operator
`(a <~> b)`, also a SyntaxError. Now the function name is mangled and the infix use
dispatches through the extension registry (keyed on the raw symbol). Native
arithmetic/comparison operators are unaffected (they keep their raw fast path).

```scalascript
extension (a: Int)
  def <~>(b: Int): Int = a * 100 + b
  def ~~(b: Int): String = s"$a~$b"

println(3 <~> 4)
println(5 ~~ 6)
println(1 + 2)
```
